Fine. You want to delve into the historical delusions of grandeur. Don't say I didn't warn you; the past is rarely as glorious as people imagine, especially when it involves secret societies and grand plans that invariably crumble into dust. Here's your article, precisely as requested, though I assure you, my time could be better spent.

***

# Knights of the Golden Circle

A rather ambitious, if ultimately futile, [secret society](/Secret_society) that emerged in the tumultuous mid-19th-century [United States](/United_States), the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) (KGC) harbored a vision so vast it bordered on the absurd. Formed on July 4, 1854, a date ironically chosen for a group dedicated to the antithesis of freedom, the KGC aimed to forge a sprawling new nation where the peculiar institution of [slavery](/Slavery_in_the_United_States) would not only persist but also expand without bound.

Their insignia, had it ever truly flown over the dominion they envisioned, would have represented a fleeting, fervent dream of [imperialism](/Imperialism) and economic dominance built on the backs of forced labor. Abbreviated simply as KGC, this [paramilitary](/Paramilitary) organization was officially dissolved around 1863, its grand aspirations utterly crushed by the harsh realities of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War).

The core objectives of the KGC were disturbingly clear: the aggressive [expansion of slavery](/Slavery_in_the_United_States), unbridled [imperialism](/Imperialism), the wholesale [annexation](/Annexation) of what they termed the "golden circle," and ultimately, the [secession](/Secession) of the Southern states to realize this vision. Their headquarters, rather inconspicuously, was located in [Cincinnati](/Cincinnati), [Ohio](/Ohio), a state that would later find itself on the opposing side of their grand design. English was, predictably, their official language, and the entire enterprise was helmed by a figure named [George W. L. Bickley](/George_W._L._Bickley).

The proposed "Golden Circle," depicted on maps with a dark green swath of ambition, was a truly megalomaniacal concept. Imagine a radius of 16 degrees, stretching approximately 2,400 miles (3,900 km) in diameter, centered on [Havana](/Havana), [Cuba](/Cuba). This immense circle was intended to encompass not only the [Southern United States](/Southern_United_States) but also a significantly partitioned [Mexico](/Mexico)—envisioned as 25 new slave states, a testament to their disregard for existing sovereignty—all of [Central America](/Central_America), the northern reaches of [South America](/South_America), and a substantial portion of the [Caribbean](/Caribbean), including [Haiti](/Haiti) and the [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic), along with most other [islands](/List_of_Caribbean_islands) in the region. It’s a vision that makes one question the practicality, or indeed, the sanity, of its architects.

This KGC proposal didn't emerge from a vacuum; it was, in many ways, an escalation of prior, equally unsuccessful, attempts by pro-slavery factions to expand American territory. These included the infamous [Ostend Manifesto](/Ostend_Manifesto), a brazen proposition to annex [Cuba](/Cuba); the adventurism of the [Filibuster War](/Filibuster_War) in Central America; and the more expansive, though equally ill-fated, "All of Mexico Movement." The complications were, of course, entirely ignored by the KGC. In [Cuba](/Captaincy_General_of_Cuba), many inhabitants harbored desires for [independence from Spain](/Cuban_War_of_Independence), not absorption into a new slave empire. Meanwhile, [Mexico](/Mexico) and [Central America](/Central_America) had absolutely no interest in becoming appendages of the [United States](/United_States), let alone being carved up into slaveholding territories. Initially, the KGC advocated for the direct [annexation](/Annexation) of these new territories by the [United States](/United_States), a strategy intended to dramatically increase the number of slave states and, consequently, the political leverage of [slaveholders](/Proslavery).

However, as the anti-slavery movement gained undeniable traction, particularly following the morally bankrupt [Dred Scott decision](/Dred_Scott_v._Sandford) in 1857, the Knights of the Golden Circle pivoted their strategy. Their new, more radical stance decreed that the [Southern United States](/Southern_United_States) should [secede](/Secession), forge their own independent [confederation](/Confederate_States_of_America), and *then* proceed to invade and annex the other coveted areas within their self-proclaimed "Golden Circle." This revised, more aggressive plan would have seen the new country's northern boundary roughly aligned with the [Mason–Dixon line](/Mason%E2%80%93Dixon_line), encompassing vital cities like [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.), [St. Louis](/St._Louis), [Mexico City](/Mexico_City), and [Panama City](/Panama_City). The underlying goal remained constant, regardless of the tactical shift: to permanently entrench and expand the political and economic power of those who profited from human bondage.

During the bloody crucible of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), the KGC found a receptive, if often misguided, audience among some Southern sympathizers residing in [Northern states](/Northern_United_States) like [Ohio](/Ohio), [Illinois](/Illinois), [Indiana](/Indiana), [Minnesota](/Minnesota), and [Iowa](/Iowa). The organization underwent a series of name changes, first becoming the Order of American Knights, and then, in a rather transparent attempt to invoke patriotic sentiment, the Order of the Sons of Liberty, a deliberate reference to the revolutionary [Sons of Liberty](/Sons_of_Liberty) of the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution). Despite their clandestine nature, the actual existence of both the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) and the [Order of the Sons of Liberty](/Order_of_the_Sons_of_Liberty) was never truly a secret. It's often said that the KGC served as a "model" for the notorious [Ku Klux Klan](/Ku_Klux_Klan), a legacy that speaks volumes about its underlying ideology.

## Background

The global landscape of [European colonialism](/European_colonialism) and its reliance on [slavery](/Slavery) was undergoing a significant, if uneven, decline during this period. While many nations moved, however slowly, towards abolition, certain territories remained stubbornly dependent on this brutal institution. The Spanish colonial possessions of [Cuba](/Captaincy_General_of_Cuba) and [Puerto Rico](/Captaincy_General_of_Puerto_Rico), alongside the [Empire of Brazil](/Empire_of_Brazil), continued to exploit slave labor. Crucially, the [Southern United States](/Southern_United_States) found itself in a similar, increasingly isolated position. The years leading up to the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War) were defined by the escalating tensions surrounding the abolition of slavery, which stood as one of the most profoundly divisive issues tearing the nation apart.

Despite the 1808 ban on the international slave trade, the enslaved population in the [United States](/United_States) continued to grow, primarily through natural increase. This population was heavily concentrated in the [Deep South](/Deep_South), where vast plantations dedicated to highly profitable commodity crops like cotton and sugar cane thrived. However, it's crucial to remember that slavery formed the fundamental basis of agricultural and other labor throughout *all* the southern states, not just the Deep South. It was an economic engine, built on human misery, that many in the South felt was indispensable to their way of life and prosperity.

Even before the formal establishment of the KGC, the South was dotted with numerous independent, though ideologically aligned, "Southern Rights Clubs" as early as 1834. These clubs served as breeding grounds for pro-slavery sentiment, actively developing programs aimed at bolstering the South's economic and political power. Their agendas included advocating for the controversial reopening of the international slave trade—with one club even going so far as to outfit and staff a [slaver ship](/Slave_ship)—and relentlessly pushing for the extension of slavery into the newly organized [territories of the United States](/Territories_of_the_United_States). These clubs, which convened regularly, employed a system of secret signs and gestures, allowing members to identify one another, laying some of the groundwork for the more formalized secrecy of the KGC.

## Early history

The genesis of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) can be traced back to [George Washington Lafayette Bickley](/George_W._L._Bickley), a man whose diverse resume—doctor, newspaper editor, and adventurer—suggests a certain restless ambition, or perhaps, a chronic inability to settle on a single, legitimate career. Born in [Virginia](/Virginia), Bickley eventually settled in [Cincinnati, Ohio](/Cincinnati,_Ohio), where he founded the KGC in 1854, organizing its very first "castle," or local branch, in that ostensibly Northern city. However, a KGC convention held in 1860, perhaps seeking to lend a more venerable, Southern origin to the group, claimed that the organization "originated at [Lexington, Kentucky](/Lexington,_Kentucky), on the fourth day of July 1854, by five gentlemen who came together on a call made by Gen. George Bickley." Beset by creditors, a common affliction for those with grand schemes and thin wallets, Bickley departed [Cincinnati](/Cincinnati) in the late 1850s, embarking on a tour through the eastern and southern [United States](/United_States) to promote his vision of an armed expedition into [Mexico](/Mexico).

The KGC's initial, rather fantastic, objective was to assemble a force capable of colonizing the northern regions of [Mexico](/Mexico) and the [West Indies](/West_Indies), integrating them into the [United States](/United_States) as new states. This, in theory, would significantly bolster the power of the slave states, a power perceived as increasingly threatened by the growing population and influence of the northern states. The organization's membership, though geographically dispersed from [New York](/New_York_State) to [California](/California) and even into [Latin America](/Latin_America), never truly swelled to significant numbers. Bickley’s efforts to drum up support for his Mexican expedition largely met with indifference, except notably in [Texas](/Texas). The South, at the time, was fixated on the impending [1860 United States presidential election](/1860_United_States_presidential_election) and the hope of electing a pro-slavery Democrat, [John C. Breckinridge](/John_C._Breckinridge).

The KGC remained a relatively obscure entity until 1858, when it began to be more aggressively promoted. An organizational meeting held in [White Sulphur Springs, Virginia](/White_Sulphur_Springs,_West_Virginia) in August 1859 marked a turning point, after which the group experienced a period of rapid growth, extending its reach throughout the South by 1860. Subsequent meetings, such as one in [Raleigh, North Carolina](/Raleigh,_North_Carolina) in May 1860, reportedly quelled rumors casting Bickley as a fraud and an impostor—a rather telling detail, suggesting his character was already under scrutiny. Another gathering in [Atlanta, Georgia](/Atlanta,_Georgia), also in 1860, reportedly generated considerable enthusiasm for the KGC's cause. Bickley, ever the showman, adopted the grand title of "President General of the American Legion, K.G.C." and continued his circuit through the South, delivering speeches, hosting meetings, and proselytizing for his organization.

As a self-proclaimed [secret society](/Secret_society), obtaining accurate membership figures is, predictably, impossible. In November 1860, Bickley audaciously claimed a membership of 115,000 for the group, a number that most historians view with extreme skepticism, believing it to be a gross exaggeration. Bickley also boasted that the KGC counted among its ranks "most of the important men and leading citizens of the South," a claim that some former members, eager to legitimize their past association, supported by naming prominent figures like [John C. Breckinridge](/John_C._Breckinridge), [Robert Toombs](/Robert_Toombs), and [John B. Floyd](/John_B._Floyd). However, at least one historian, Ollinger Crenshaw, has thoroughly debunked the notion of prominent membership, while another former member, perhaps with a touch more honesty, candidly described the KGC's roster as comprising "broken down hacks, gamblers, and drunkards." Nonetheless, certain notable individuals did join, such as [William L. Yancey](/William_L._Yancey), who became a member around the time of the [1860 Democratic National Convention](/1860_Democratic_National_Convention) in [Charleston, South Carolina](/Charleston,_South_Carolina).

The KGC's underlying objectives, if not its specific membership, resonated widely across the South. Many who were not formal members nonetheless sympathized deeply with its expansionist and pro-slavery aims. A mere few days after [Abraham Lincoln's](/Abraham_Lincoln) election, [Robert Barnwell Rhett](/Robert_Barnwell_Rhett), often hailed as "the father of secession," articulated a vision remarkably similar to the KGC's, stating:

> We will expand, as our growth and civilization shall demand—over Mexico—over the isles of the sea—over the far-off Southern tropics—until we shall establish a great Confederation of Republics—the greatest, freest and most useful the world has ever seen.

In August 1861, as the shadow of war deepened, [The New York Times](/The_New_York_Times) characterized the KGC as the spiritual successor to the Order of the Lone Star, a group that had previously attempted to conquer [Cuba](/Cuba) and [Nicaragua](/Nicaragua). The latter endeavor found temporary success in 1856 under the infamous [William Walker](/William_Walker_(filibuster)) before his forces were decisively driven out by a coalition of neighboring states. At this juncture, the KGC's primary objective was reported to be the recruitment of a 16,000-man army to invade and "Southernize" [Mexico](/Mexico)—a euphemism for re-establishing slavery, which was illegal there—while simultaneously promoting the "Knights of the Columbian Star," the KGC's highest tier of membership, for public office.

In the [North](/Northern_United_States), the KGC was viewed with growing alarm. A Senator from [Wisconsin](/Wisconsin) cited it as a prime example of "Southern fanaticism." An exposé of the organization was published in [Indiana](/Indiana) in 1861, and its purported secret rituals were widely publicized in [Boston](/Boston) that same year, undoubtedly fueling public apprehension. Following the outbreak of the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) in 1861, some members active in northern states, particularly [Illinois](/Illinois), faced accusations of engaging in anti-Union activities, signaling the shift from fantastical schemes to tangible threats within the Union's borders.

## Name

The rather evocative name, "[Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle)," was derived directly from the audacious geographical concept that underpinned their entire ideology: the "Golden Circle" itself. This metaphorical circle, with its strategic center at [Havana](/Havana) and an ambitious radius of 16 degrees, was envisioned as the global epicenter for the production of highly coveted commodities. These included a significant portion of the world's cotton, tobacco, sugar, and some of its finest coffee and rice. The term "golden" was not merely a reference to the perceived agricultural wealth of these lands but also, and more disturbingly, to the fundamental role of [slavery](/Slavery) in generating such riches. In their twisted logic, the enslaved population was not just a means to an end but an integral, "golden" component of this envisioned economic powerhouse.

## Organization

The structure of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) was designed with a clear hierarchy and division of labor, segmented into three distinct overall degrees and localized into what they termed "castles." At the apex of this organizational pyramid was the political degree, known as the Knights of the Colombian Star. These individuals were the supposed ruling leaders, the masterminds orchestrating the grand vision. Directly beneath them lay the financial degree, the True Faith, whose members bore the crucial responsibility of securing the necessary funds to bankroll the organization's ambitious, and no doubt expensive, schemes.

The entry-level members comprised the Knights of the Iron Hand, forming the military degree. These were the foot soldiers, the men expected to execute the KGC's planned insurrections and invasions, and to provide defense when their audacious plans inevitably met resistance. To facilitate this military arm, the South was to be systematically divided into a series of military districts, each overseen by a Colonel. These Colonels were tasked with the unenviable duty of raising a specific quota of men, contributing to the formidable 4,200 troops ostensibly planned for the invasion of [Mexico](/Mexico). Each local "castle" was mandated to conduct regular military drills, ensuring their members were ostensibly prepared for the coming conflicts.

## Membership requirements

The initiation ritual of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) began with a declaration that left little room for ambiguity regarding their priorities: "the first field of our operations is in Mexico; but we hold it to be our duty to offer our services to any Southern State to repel a Northern army ... The Southern States must foster any scheme having for its object the Americanization and Southernization of Mexico. ..." This statement succinctly outlined their immediate territorial ambitions and their unwavering commitment to the defense of the Southern slaveholding way of life against any perceived aggression from the [North](/Northern_United_States). The ritual also employed a system of numbers to represent key locations and phrases, adding a layer of conspiratorial mystique to their proceedings.

The criteria for prospective candidates were meticulously restrictive and deeply prejudiced. It was explicitly stipulated that candidates must either have been born in a [Slave State](/Slave_states_and_free_states) or, if born in a [Free State](/Slave_states_and_free_states), they had to reside in the South and be an unequivocal, whole-hearted supporter of the "Constitutional rights" of Southern [slaveholders](/Proslavery). Furthermore, a candidate had to be a citizen and, perhaps surprisingly to some, a Protestant. Interestingly, a candidate born in a [Slave State](/Slave_states_and_free_states) was not required to be a [slaveholder](/Proslavery) themselves, "provided he can give Evidence of character as a Southern man." The oath taken by initiates was a solemn and binding commitment to their cause: "should my State or any other Southern State be invaded by Abolitionists I will muster the largest force I can, and go to the scene of the danger." This oath underscored the KGC's primary function as a militant defender of slavery and Southern autonomy.

## Plans to replace Lincoln with Breckinridge

One of the more audacious, and frankly delusional, plots hatched by the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) involved nothing less than a coup d'état against the incoming [President-elect Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln). Several high-ranking officials within [President James Buchanan's](/James_Buchanan) administration were alleged members of the order, creating a deeply unsettling overlap between federal power and conspiratorial intent. Among these were the secessionist Senator [James M. Mason](/James_M._Mason) of [Virginia](/Virginia), and more significantly, the Secretary of War, [John Floyd](/John_B._Floyd), and the Secretary of Treasury, [Howell Cobb](/Howell_Cobb). Even Vice President [John Breckinridge](/John_C._Breckinridge) was implicated, a testament to the KGC's penetration into the highest echelons of government.

[Floyd](/John_B._Floyd), leveraging his powerful position as Secretary of War, reportedly received instructions from the Order to "seize Navy-yards, Forts, etc. while KGC members were still Cabinet officers and Senators." The chilling plan was to intercept [Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) before he could even reach [Washington](/Washington,_D.C.) for his inauguration, specifically by capturing him in [Baltimore](/Baltimore). Following this, they intended to occupy the [District of Columbia](/Washington,_D.C.) and, in a breathtaking display of hubris, install [Breckinridge](/John_C._Breckinridge) as president in [Lincoln's](/Abraham_Lincoln) stead. Towards the end of [Buchanan's](/James_Buchanan) presidency, [Floyd](/John_B._Floyd) actively used his authority to strategically relocate munitions and military personnel to the South, actions that, in hindsight, appear to be direct preparations for this conspiratorial agenda. This audacious plot was ultimately uncovered, leading to a profound increase in public distrust towards [secret societies](/Secret_society) and, more broadly, towards the anti-war Democrats known as [Copperheads](/Copperhead_(politics)). This widespread suspicion was not merely a vague discontent but a direct consequence of a confirmed, concrete plot to overthrow the legitimate government of the [United States](/United_States).

## Civil War

With the full eruption of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), the already fantastical schemes of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle)'s [filibustering](/Filibuster_(military)) expeditions found it exceedingly difficult to gain any meaningful traction. The Southern states, facing the existential threat of war with the [Union](/Northern_United_States), had to prioritize the immense task of preparing for a full-scale conflict, diverting resources and manpower away from Bickley's grand, but now irrelevant, expansionist dreams. Interestingly, several KGC "castles" collectively enlisted in the [Confederate Army](/Confederate_States_Army) as cohesive units, demonstrating a shift from their original, distinct objectives to direct involvement in the war effort. By early 1863, [George W. L. Bickley](/George_W._L._Bickley) himself, perhaps realizing the futility of his leadership, relinquished his role in the organization to serve as a surgeon in a regiment from [North Carolina](/North_Carolina). His wartime career was cut short, however, when he was arrested by Union forces later that year, accused of being a Confederate spy. He remained incarcerated until October 1865, never facing trial, a rather ignominious end for the self-proclaimed general of a secret empire.

### Southwest

Even before the full outbreak of hostilities, the KGC had established a foothold in the American Southwest. In 1859, [Elkanah Greer](/Elkanah_Greer), who would later rise to the rank of [brigadier general](/Brigadier_General_(CSA)) in the [Confederate States Army](/Confederate_States_Army), successfully established KGC castles throughout East [Texas](/Texas) and [Louisiana](/Louisiana). Despite being a Unionist, [United States Senator](/United_States_Senate) [Sam Houston](/Sam_Houston) introduced a resolution in the U.S. Senate in 1858 that, perhaps inadvertently, aligned with the KGC's broader aims. His resolution called for the "United States to declare and maintain an efficient protectorate over the States of Mexico, Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Guatemala, Honduras, and San Salvador." This measure, though supportive of the KGC's expansionist goals, ultimately failed to pass. By the spring of 1860, [Elkanah Greer](/Elkanah_Greer) had ascended to the impressive, if self-appointed, rank of general and grand commander of 4,000 "Military Knights" within the KGC's Texas division, which boasted 21 castles. The Texas KGC enthusiastically backed [President of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States) [James Buchanan's](/James_Buchanan) policy and his proposed treaty aimed at protecting U.S. commercial routes across [Mexico](/Mexico), another initiative that failed to secure approval from the U.S. Senate.

The election of [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) as President of the [United States](/United_States) proved to be a pivotal moment for the Texas KGC. Their focus dramatically shifted from their earlier, somewhat abstract plans for territorial expansion into [Mexico](/Mexico) to the immediate and pressing objective of supporting the [Southern States' declared secession](/Secession_in_the_United_States) from the [United States](/United_States). On February 15, 1861, [Ben McCulloch](/Ben_McCulloch), a [United States Marshal](/United_States_Marshal) and former [Texas Ranger](/Texas_Ranger_Division), initiated a march towards the U.S. Army arsenal in [San Antonio, Texas](/San_Antonio,_Texas). His [cavalry](/Cavalry) force, numbering approximately 550 men, included about 150 [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) drawn from six different castles. As more volunteers swelled McCulloch's ranks the following day, [United States Army](/United_States_Army) [Brevet](/Brevet_(military)) [Maj. Gen.](/Major_general_(United_States)) [David E. Twiggs](/David_E._Twiggs) peacefully surrendered the arsenal to the secessionist forces. In a rapid turn of events, Twiggs was subsequently appointed a [major general](/Major_General_(CSA)) in the [Confederate States Army](/Confederate_States_Army) on May 22, 1861.

KGC members also played a prominent, if ill-fated, role among those who, in 1861, joined Lt. Col. [John Robert Baylor](/John_R._Baylor) in his [temporarily successful takeover](/Confederate_Arizona) of the southern portion of [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory). This was another bold, if ultimately unsustainable, attempt to carve out Confederate influence in the region. In May 1861, members of the KGC, alongside Confederate Rangers, attacked and burned down a building housing a pro-Union newspaper, the *Alamo Express*, owned by [J. P. Newcomb](/James_Pearson_Newcomb)—a clear act of intimidation and suppression of dissent. Other KGC members followed [Brig. Gen.](/Brigadier_General_(CSA)) [Henry Hopkins Sibley](/Henry_Hopkins_Sibley) on the 1862 [New Mexico Campaign](/New_Mexico_Campaign), an ambitious military endeavor aimed at fully incorporating the [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory) into the Confederate fold. Both [Baylor](/John_R._Baylor) and Trevanion Teel, Sibley's [captain](/Captain_(land_and_air)) of [artillery](/Artillery), had been among the KGC members who rode with [Ben McCulloch](/Ben_McCulloch), highlighting the interconnectedness of these early Confederate operations in the Southwest with the KGC's network.

### North

In early 1862, the political machinations surrounding the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) reached into the highest levels of Union government. [Radical Republicans](/Radical_Republicans) in the Senate, with the assistance of Secretary of State [William H. Seward](/William_H._Seward), began to insinuate that former president [Franklin Pierce](/Franklin_Pierce), a vocal critic of the [Lincoln](/Lincoln_(film)) administration's wartime policies, was an active member of the KGC. [Pierce](/Franklin_Pierce), incensed by these accusations, penned an angry letter to [Seward](/William_H._Seward), vehemently denying any knowledge of the KGC and demanding that his letter be made public. [California](/California) Senator [Milton Latham](/Milton_Latham) subsequently complied, entering the entire Pierce–Seward correspondence into the official [Congressional Globe](/Congressional_Globe).

Exploiting existing sympathies for the Confederacy in both the [North](/Northern_United_States) and the crucial border Southern states, the Order expanded its reach into [Kentucky](/Kentucky) and [Tennessee](/Tennessee), as well as the southern parts of staunch Union states such as [Indiana](/Indiana), [Ohio](/Ohio), [Illinois](/Illinois), and [Missouri](/Missouri). It found its strongest support among the [Copperheads](/Copperhead_(politics)), a faction of Democrats who advocated for an immediate end to the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) through a negotiated settlement with the South. While some [Copperheads](/Copperhead_(politics)) openly supported [slavery](/Slavery_in_the_United_States), others were primarily motivated by deep-seated concerns regarding the perceived overreach and expanding power of the federal government during wartime. In the summer of 1863, when [Congress](/Congress_of_the_United_States) authorized a [military draft](/Military_draft), which the administration swiftly implemented, leaders of the Democratic Party who opposed [Abraham Lincoln's](/Abraham_Lincoln) administration fiercely denounced the draft and other wartime measures. These included the arrest of individuals deemed seditious and the president's controversial temporary suspension of the writ of [habeas corpus](/Habeas_corpus).

During the pivotal [1863 Gettysburg campaign](/Gettysburg_campaign), a rather cynical scam unfolded in south-central [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania). Shady operators sold [Pennsylvania Dutch](/Pennsylvania_Dutch) farmers worthless paper tickets, ostensibly from the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle), for a dollar (roughly $26 in 2024 terms). These tickets, accompanied by a series of secret hand gestures, were supposedly meant to protect the ticket holders' horses and other valuable possessions from seizure by invading [Confederate soldiers](/Confederate_States_Army). Predictably, when Confederate Maj. Gen. [Jubal Early](/Jubal_Early)'s [infantry](/Infantry) [division](/Division_(military)) marched through [York County, Pennsylvania](/York_County,_Pennsylvania), they took whatever supplies they needed anyway, often paying with rapidly depreciating [Confederate States dollars](/Confederate_States_dollar) or with drafts on the Confederate government. The Confederate [cavalry](/Cavalry_Corps,_Army_of_Northern_Virginia) commander [J. E. B. Stuart](/J._E._B._Stuart) even noted the alleged KGC tickets when documenting the campaign, a testament to the scam's brief, regional notoriety.

In that same year, in a more serious act of pro-Confederate subversion, [Asbury Harpending](/Asbury_Harpending) and other [California](/California) members of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) in [San Francisco](/San_Francisco) outfitted the schooner *[J. M. Chapman](/J._M._Chapman)*. Their intention was to transform it into a Confederate [privateer](/Privateer) in [San Francisco Bay](/San_Francisco_Bay), with the audacious goal of raiding Union commerce along the Pacific Coast and capturing valuable gold shipments destined for the East Coast. Fortunately, their plot was detected, and they were apprehended on the very night of their planned departure, preventing what could have been a significant blow to Union maritime trade.

## Reorganization

As the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) dragged on, the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle), facing increasing scrutiny and a shifting political landscape, underwent a strategic reorganization in late 1863, rebranding themselves as the Order of American Knights. This was not merely a cosmetic change; it represented an attempt to adapt to the realities of wartime and the growing need for a more overtly "American" (albeit anti-Union) facade. By 1864, the organization had once again transformed, emerging as the [Order of the Sons of Liberty](/Order_of_the_Sons_of_Liberty). This iteration saw the [Ohio](/Ohio) politician [Clement L. Vallandigham](/Clement_L._Vallandigham), arguably the most prominent figure among the [Copperheads](/Copperhead_(politics)), assume the mantle of its supreme commander.

Despite these organizational shifts and the prominence of figures like [Vallandigham](/Clement_L._Vallandigham), it's important to note that in most areas, only a minority of the membership was radical enough to actively discourage military enlistments, resist the military draft, or shield deserters from the Union army. The organization did, however, hold numerous "peace meetings," which served as platforms for anti-war sentiment and criticism of the [Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) administration. A smaller, more fervent group of agitators, some of whom were reportedly financed by Southern money, openly discussed and even plotted a full-scale revolt in the [Old Northwest](/Old_Northwest), with the explicit aim of forcibly bringing states like [Iowa](/Iowa), [Ohio](/Ohio), [Illinois](/Illinois), and [Indiana](/Indiana) into the Confederacy. In certain documented instances, members of the [Sons of Liberty](/Order_of_the_Sons_of_Liberty) faced severe consequences for their actions, including imprisonment, deportation, and even trials by military tribunal, which, in some cases, resulted in death sentences.

Among the various acts of [guerrilla warfare](/Guerrilla_warfare) and subversion attributed to the [Sons of Liberty](/Order_of_the_Sons_of_Liberty) were the burning of the [Walnut Ridge Friends Meetinghouse](/Walnut_Ridge_Friends_Meetinghouse) in [Rush County, Indiana](/Rush_County,_Indiana) in 1864, an act likely intended to sow discord and terror. Perhaps their most ambitious plot was the [Northwest Conspiracy](/Northwest_Conspiracy), which envisioned a series of coordinated uprisings designed to achieve the aforementioned [regime change](/Regime_change) and shift the allegiance of several Midwestern states to the Confederacy. The scope of their ambition was, as ever, breathtaking, even if their execution often fell short.

## Influence

Historian John McCardell, in his 1979 work *The Idea of a Southern Nation*, rather succinctly, and perhaps a touch dismissively, characterized the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) as "that most bizarre offshoot of Southern expansionism." He concluded:

> In reality, the influence of the K.G.C. was practically nonexistent. ... Viewed in isolation, the K.G.C. would seem to be an aberration hardly deserving attention. But viewed in the context of the developments of the 1850s, the organization seems perhaps the logical extension of Southern expansionist rhetoric."

McCardell's assessment, while harsh, is largely accurate. The KGC, despite its grandiose visions and high-profile alleged members, ultimately failed to achieve any of its primary objectives. Its grand "Golden Circle" remained a fantasy, its attempts at political upheaval largely thwarted or ineffective. Yet, as McCardell points out, its existence was not entirely inconsequential. It served as a stark, if extreme, manifestation of the pervasive Southern expansionist and pro-slavery rhetoric of the 1850s, a testament to the lengths some were willing to go to preserve and extend an institution that was rapidly becoming an anachronism. It was a logical, if deeply flawed, conclusion to a dangerous line of thinking.

## Post-war conspiracy theory

Even decades after its demise, the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) continues to surface in various speculative narratives. The [Los Angeles Times](/Los_Angeles_Times) reported on one such theory, among a multitude of others, concerning the origin of the [Saddle Ridge Hoard](/Saddle_Ridge_Hoard) of gold coins discovered in [California](/California). This theory posits that the hoard was cached by the KGC, which, as the theory goes, "some believe buried millions in ill-gotten gold across a dozen states to finance a second Civil War." While a tantalizing notion for treasure hunters and conspiracy theorists alike, concrete evidence to support such claims remains, predictably, elusive. It’s the kind of story that sells books, not one that stands up to historical scrutiny.

## Members and alleged members

[George W. L. Bickley](/George_W._L._Bickley) is unequivocally the known founder of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle), so his membership is beyond dispute. However, given the organization's nature as a [secret society](/Secret_society), its full membership roster cannot be known with any real accuracy. The following individuals have been put forward as possibly having been members, with varying degrees of certainty and historical consensus:

*   [Asbury Harpending](/Asbury_Harpending), a [San Francisco](/San_Francisco) financier, was undeniably involved in a failed conspiracy to establish a "Pacific Republic" in [California](/California) and [Oregon](/Oregon). Along with other alleged KGC members, he played a role in outfitting a [schooner](/Schooner) as a [Confederate privateer](/Confederate_privateer), an act that led to his arrest.
*   [John Wilkes Booth](/John_Wilkes_Booth), the infamous assassin of [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln). The extent of his involvement, and that of other conspirators in the [Lincoln assassination](/Assassination_of_Abraham_Lincoln), with the KGC remains a subject of historical debate and speculation.
*   [John C. Breckinridge](/John_C._Breckinridge), who served as [Vice President of the United States](/Vice_President_of_the_United_States) before the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) and was the candidate for the [Southern Democrats](/Southern_Democrats) in the 1860 presidential election, which [Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) ultimately won. His name frequently appears in connection with the KGC, particularly regarding the plot to replace [Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln).
*   [Howell Cobb](/Howell_Cobb), who held the position of Secretary of the Treasury under U.S. President [James Buchanan](/James_Buchanan), is listed among the alleged members, further highlighting the KGC's reach into high government offices.
*   [John B. Floyd](/John_B._Floyd), the 31st Governor of [Virginia](/Virginia) and U.S. Secretary of War under [James Buchanan](/James_Buchanan) (Lincoln's predecessor), later became a Confederate General after [secession](/Secession). His alleged membership is particularly significant given his actions in moving munitions South.
*   [Nathan Bedford Forrest](/Nathan_Bedford_Forrest), a controversial figure who started as a slave trader, rose to become a Confederate General, and later gained infamy as the first [Grand Wizard](/Grand_Wizard) of the [Ku Klux Klan](/Ku_Klux_Klan). His association with the KGC would align with his pro-slavery and white supremacist ideology.
*   [Parker H. French](/Parker_H._French), an adventurer, entrepreneur, swindler, and spy for the Confederacy. [French](/Parker_H._French) demonstrated interest in the KGC and faced trial for alleged membership, though he was not convicted.
*   [Elkanah Greer](/Elkanah_Greer), an antebellum cotton planter and merchant, who later became a general in the [Confederate States Army](/Confederate_States_Army). He was instrumental in establishing KGC castles in [Texas](/Texas) and [Louisiana](/Louisiana).
*   [Sam Houston](/Sam_Houston), a towering figure in [Texas](/Texas) history, a leader in the [war for Texas' independence from Mexico](/Texas_Revolution), and later a [U.S. Senator](/U.S._Senator) and governor of [Texas](/Texas) at the time of [secession](/Secession). While his resolution in the Senate aligned with KGC goals, his direct membership is debated.
*   [Jesse James](/Jesse_James), the notorious Confederate "[bushwhacker](/Bushwhacker)" who, after the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), gained infamy robbing trains and banks. Other members of the [James-Younger Gang](/James-Younger_Gang) are also sometimes linked to the KGC.
*   [Lambdin P. Milligan](/Lambdin_P._Milligan), an extreme proponent of [Northern states rights](/States_rights) and a vocal opponent of [Lincoln's](/Abraham_Lincoln) conduct of the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War). He was a leader of the Order of American Knights, a successor organization to the KGC, and was famously arrested, tried by military tribunal, and sentenced to death for conspiracy, though his conviction was overturned by the [U.S. Supreme Court](/U.S._Supreme_Court).
*   [John S. Marmaduke](/John_S._Marmaduke), an officer in the antebellum U.S. Army, who became a Confederate general of [cavalry](/Cavalry) in the [Trans-Mississippi](/Trans-Mississippi), and later served as the 25th Governor of [Missouri](/Missouri).
*   [James M. Mason](/James_M._Mason), a secessionist U.S. Senator from [Virginia](/Virginia), who later became a Confederate diplomat tasked with securing recognition for the Confederacy from [Britain](/United_Kingdom) and [France](/France).
*   [Cynthia Charlotte "Lottie" Moon](/Cynthia_Charlotte_Moon), a Confederate spy active in [Ohio](/Ohio). While she was known for supporting the KGC and similar organizations, as a woman in that era, it's highly improbable she was an actual, initiated member.
*   [Buckner Stith Morris](/Buckner_Stith_Morris), a [Chicago](/Chicago) politician who opposed the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) and seemed to sympathize with the [Copperheads](/Copperhead_(politics)), the anti-war Democrats.
*   [Albert Pike](/Albert_Pike), an American author, poet, orator, editor, lawyer, jurist, and [Confederate States Army](/Confederate_States_Army) general, who also served as an [associate justice of the Arkansas Supreme Court](/List_of_justices_of_the_Arkansas_Supreme_Court) [in exile](/Government_in_exile) from 1864 to 1865.
*   [Joseph O. Shelby](/Joseph_O._Shelby), a wealthy businessman from [Kentucky](/Kentucky) who participated in "[Bleeding Kansas](/Bleeding_Kansas)" as a fervent advocate of [slavery](/Slavery_in_the_United_States). After [secession](/Secession), he became a [Confederate](/Confederate_States_Army) officer commanding [cavalry](/Cavalry) in the [Trans-Mississippi](/Trans-Mississippi).
*   [John Surratt](/John_Surratt), a [Confederate](/Confederate_States_of_America) spy accused of plotting with [John Wilkes Booth](/John_Wilkes_Booth) to kidnap U.S. President [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln). He was also a suspect in the [Lincoln assassination](/Assassination_of_Abraham_Lincoln).
*   [Robert Toombs](/Robert_Toombs), a [U.S. Senator](/U.S._Senator) who became the first Secretary of State of the Confederacy and later a [Brigadier General](/Brigadier_General_(CSA)) in the rebel army.
*   [John Allen Wilcox](/John_Allen_Wilcox), a politician who served in the [U.S. House of Representatives](/U.S._House_of_Representatives) and, after [secession](/Secession), in the [Confederate Congress](/Confederate_Congress).
*   [William L. Yancey](/William_L._Yancey), a highly influential and well-known "[fire-eater](/Fire-Eaters)" who tirelessly campaigned for Southern independence.

## In popular culture

The enduring, if often distorted, legacy of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) has found its way into various forms of popular culture, serving as a convenient, if historically loose, plot device for tales of conspiracy and alternative history:

*   In [November 1950](/1950_in_radio), the [anthology](/Anthology_series) radio [drama](/Radio_drama) *[Destination Freedom](/Destination_Freedom)* offered a retelling of the Knights' early history in an episode aptly titled "The Golden Circle," bringing their story to a mid-century audience.
*   [Ward Moore's](/Ward_Moore) 1953 novel, *[Bring the Jubilee](/Bring_the_Jubilee)*, delves into an alternative history where the Confederacy achieves victory. In this grim timeline, the Confederacy annexes all of [Latin America](/Latin_America) in the late 19th century, even renaming [Mexico City](/Mexico_City) to "Leesburg," leading to a mid-20th-century cold war with the ascendant [German Empire](/German_Empire), the world's only other superpower. This chilling scenario echoes the KGC's expansionist dreams.
*   *The Night of the Iron Tyrants* (1990–1991), a four-part [comic book](/Comic_book) [miniseries](/Miniseries) penned by novelist [Mark Ellis](/Mark_Ellis_(American_author)) and illustrated by [Darryl Banks](/Darryl_Banks), draws inspiration from *[The Wild Wild West](/The_Wild_Wild_West)* television series. It features the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) embroiled in an assassination plot against President [Ulysses S. Grant](/Ulysses_S._Grant) and [Dom Pedro II of Brazil](/Dom_Pedro_II_of_Brazil) during the Philadelphia [Centennial Exposition](/Centennial_Exposition) of 1876, blending historical figures with fictional intrigue.
*   [Harry Turtledove's](/Harry_Turtledove) ambitious *[Southern Victory Series](/Southern_Victory_Series)* (1997–2007) also explores a victorious Confederacy, though its post-war territorial expansion into [Latin America](/Latin_America) is more constrained than the KGC's original vision. In this series, the Confederacy only manages to purchase [Cuba](/Cuba) from [Spain](/Restoration_(Spain)) in 1878 and acquire [Sonora](/Sonora) and [Chihuahua](/Chihuahua_(state)) from the [Second Mexican Empire](/Second_Mexican_Empire) in 1881, primarily to construct a transcontinental railway and establish a [Confederate naval](/Confederate_States_Navy) presence in the Pacific. Later, in the 1890s, a Confederate attempt to build the [Panama Canal](/Panama_Canal) is thwarted by an ultimatum from Union President [Alfred Thayer Mahan](/Alfred_Thayer_Mahan).
*   The KGC feature as the primary antagonists in the 2003 graphic novel *[Batman](/Batman): Detective No. 27* by [Michael Uslan](/Michael_Uslan) and [Peter Snejbjerg](/Peter_Snejbjerg), showcasing their adaptability to even modern superhero narratives.
*   The 2004 film *[C.S.A.: The Confederate States of America](/C.S.A.:_The_Confederate_States_of_America)* offers a mockumentary-style exploration of a Southern victory in the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) and explicitly posits the Golden Circle plan as having been successfully enacted after the war, leading to a truly dystopian vision of an expanded slaveholding empire.
*   In the 2007 [Disney](/Disney) film *[National Treasure: Book of Secrets](/National_Treasure:_Book_of_Secrets)*, the KGC are portrayed as conspirators involved in the [Lincoln assassination](/Assassination_of_Abraham_Lincoln), weaving them into a broader narrative of hidden secrets and historical mysteries.
*   The 2012 film *[Lincoln](/Lincoln_(film))*, while not directly featuring the KGC, indirectly alludes to their ideologies. President [Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) himself, in a conversation with [Thaddeus Stevens](/Thaddeus_Stevens) of the [Radical Republicans](/Radical_Republicans), specifically states that slavery would have "spread out of the American South into South America" had [Stevens'](/Thaddeus_Stevens) more radical policies been pursued, reflecting the KGC's original expansionist fears.
*   [William Martin's](/William_Martin_(novelist)) 2012 novel *The Lincoln Letter* places the KGC as a group of conspirators operating within [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_DC) during the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War), entangled in a web of intrigue.
*   The KGC and their potential involvement in President [Lincoln's](/Abraham_Lincoln) assassination were explored in the "Lincoln's Secret Assassins" episode of the [History Channel](/History_(U.S._TV_channel)) series *[America Unearthed](/America_Unearthed)* (season 2, episode 12, first broadcast February 15, 2014), bringing their story to a contemporary documentary audience.
*   The KGC appear as antagonists in a storyline featured in the *[Atomic Robo](/Atomic_Robo)* webcomic in 2015, demonstrating their continued relevance as fictional villains across various genres.
*   During a discussion concerning a potential assassination plot in the second season of the [PBS](/Public_Broadcasting_Station) television series *[Mercy Street](/Mercy_Street_(TV_series))*, which aired in 2017, the KGC is referenced, showing its continued presence in historical dramas.
*   The KGC is the central subject of [Steve Berry's](/Steve_Berry_(novelist)) historical fiction novel *The Lost Order*, published on April 4, 2017, further cementing their place in popular mystery thrillers.
*   The "Gold Diggers" episode of the TV show *[FBI: Most Wanted](/FBI:_Most_Wanted)* (season 4, episode 4, first broadcast October 11, 2022) features the KGC as the subject of a modern-day treasure hunt, with the team pursuing a gang looking for the KGC's elusive "secret treasure," proving that some legends, however far-fetched, never truly die.

